@flexiarg proof-search/sorry-boundary-clustering
@title Cluster Sorry Boundaries; Extend Where the Clusters Point
@sigils [∴/🗺]
@keywords sorry, proof hole, blocker, cluster, boundary atlas, mathlib extension, cross-problem, formalization, lean
@audience anyone driving a formalization corpus with many partial proofs
@tone procedural
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a proof corpus has many partial proofs, do not treat each sorry as a private blocker: CLUSTER the sorry boundaries by type across the corpus, and direct effort at the clusters — one targeted library extension (lemma, tactic, instance) closes many problems at once. The atlas of failures, read as intensities, is the intervention map.

  + context: A corpus of formalization attempts (proofs, exercises, ports)
    accumulates partial proofs, each stopped at one or more sorries. Effort
    naturally flows to grinding individual proofs forward.

  + IF:
      You have many partial proofs, each blocked at a sorry (a typed hole
      the proof needs filled).

  + HOWEVER:
      The blockers REPEAT: the same missing lemma family, the same absent
      instance, the same tactic gap appears across otherwise-unrelated
      problems — but nobody sees the repetition because each sorry is
      examined only inside its own proof.

  + THEN:
      Build the sorry-boundary atlas: extract every sorry's interface (what
      it wants, in what context), cluster by type/shape across the whole
      corpus, and rank clusters by how many problems each would unblock.
      Spend effort on the top cluster's LIBRARY extension, not on the
      hardest single proof.

  + BECAUSE:
      Sorry boundaries are not independent — they are samples from the
      library's gap distribution. A targeted extension at a dense cluster
      pays across the corpus (expected information gain over the corpus,
      not the instance); grinding one proof pays once.

  + canonical-instance:
      M-diagramprover (futon3c): 39 partial Lean proofs over the 489-problem
      prelim corpus, ~30 with diagnosed sorry boundaries, 12 recurring
      formalization patterns identified — the readiness condition for the
      Bayesian model that ranks Mathlib extensions by expected impact.
      Authored as a proof-search seed 2026-07-05 (the library-gap finding:
      a well-formed diagramprover ψ drew a size-1 cascade because no
      proof-search vocabulary existed here).
